+const summary = `Dataset ds001_aml contained ${N} patients and one binary outcome, objective_response. The overall response rate was ${fmt(overall, 4)}. I decoded the local Parquet file and tested main effects, subgroup heterogeneity, and interactions using response-rate contrasts and linear probability models; p-values are exploratory and mostly unadjusted unless explicitly described as adjusted.\n\nMain effects: feature_027 had the strongest monotone association. Response fell from ${fmt(by027[0].p)} at level 0 to ${fmt(by027[1].p)} at level 1 and ${fmt(by027[2].p)} at level 2, with an effect of ${fmt(trend027.beta, 4)} per level (p=${sci(trend027.pValue)}). The strongest binary positive main effects were feature_025 (effect ${fmt(b025.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(b025.pValue)}), feature_015 (effect ${fmt(b015.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(b015.pValue)}), and feature_023 (effect ${fmt(b023.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(b023.pValue)}). Negative binary main effects were feature_001 (effect ${fmt(b001.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(b001.pValue)}) and feature_032 (effect ${fmt(b032.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(b032.pValue)}). Feature_044 showed no meaningful main effect per 10 units (effect ${fmt(o044.beta, 5)}, p=${sci(o044.pValue)}).\n\nContinuous features: feature_004, feature_031, feature_059, feature_033, and feature_053 all showed significant univariable associations. The directions were lower response with higher feature_004 (effect ${fmt(o004.beta, 4)} per unit), lower response with higher feature_031 (effect ${fmt(o031.beta, 4)} per 10 units), higher response with higher feature_059 (effect ${fmt(o059.beta, 4)} per unit), lower response with higher feature_033 (effect ${fmt(o033.beta, 5)} per unit), and lower response with higher feature_053 (effect ${fmt(o053.beta, 4)} per 10 units). In the extended adjusted model, feature_025, feature_027, feature_004, and feature_059 retained their directions; feature_044 stayed null.\n\nThe most important interaction pattern involved feature_015, feature_025, and feature_023. Pairwise screens showed large positive interactions among these variables, especially feature_015 x feature_025 (DID ${fmt(did15025.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did15025.pValue)}), feature_025 x feature_023 (DID ${fmt(did25023.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did25023.pValue)}), and feature_015 x feature_023 (DID ${fmt(did15023.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did15023.pValue)}). Subgroup testing refined this: feature_015 had almost no effect when feature_025=0 (effect ${fmt(sub015in0250.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(sub015in0250.pValue)}) but a large positive effect when feature_025=1 (effect ${fmt(sub015in0251.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(sub015in0251.pValue)}).\n\nThe refined multivariable interaction model showed that the apparent pairwise effects were largely driven by a three-way pattern. Patients with feature_015=1, feature_025=1, and feature_023=1 had response ${fmt(triple.p1)} (n=${triple.n1}), versus ${fmt(triple.p0)} among all other patients, an absolute difference of ${fmt(triple.effect, 4)}. In a model containing all three main effects, all pairwise terms, the three-way term, feature_001, feature_032, and feature_027, the three-way coefficient was ${fmt(threeModel.get("feature_015_x_feature_025_x_feature_023").beta, 4)} (p=${sci(threeModel.get("feature_015_x_feature_025_x_feature_023").pValue)}), while the feature_015 x feature_025 pairwise term became nonsignificant. This supports a high-response subgroup defined by simultaneous positivity for all three features rather than isolated positivity for only one or two.\n\nNegative-effect heterogeneity was also present. feature_001 attenuated the feature_025 association (interaction ${fmt(did001025.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did001025.pValue)}), feature_032 attenuated the feature_025 association (interaction ${fmt(did025032.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did025032.pValue)}), and feature_032 attenuated the feature_015 association (interaction ${fmt(did015032.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did015032.pValue)}). The two negative main-effect features feature_001 and feature_032 did not show evidence of an additional negative interaction with each other (interaction ${fmt(did001032.effect, 4)}, p=${sci(did001032.pValue)}).\n\nSubgroup checks across feature_027 did not show statistically significant modification of the feature_015 effect by feature_027 (interaction ${fmt(inter015027.beta, 4)}, p=${sci(inter015027.pValue)}). Nominal continuous-by-binary interactions were detected for feature_044 by feature_066 (slope difference ${fmt(inter044066.beta, 4)} per 10 units, p=${sci(inter044066.pValue)}) and feature_053 by feature_068 (slope difference ${fmt(inter053068.beta, 4)} per 10 units, p=${sci(inter053068.pValue)}), but these were weaker exploratory findings.\n\nOverall conclusion: objective_response in this cohort is dominated by a strong low-response gradient across feature_027, independent continuous adverse associations involving feature_004, feature_031, feature_033, and feature_053, a positive continuous association with feature_059, and a striking high-response subgroup where feature_015, feature_025, and feature_023 are all present. The strongest treatment-biomarker-like relationship is the three-feature interaction; isolated positivity for only one or two of those features does not reproduce the same high response rate.\n`;
+
+fs.writeFileSync("transcript.json", JSON.stringify(transcript, null, 2) + "\n", "utf8");
+fs.writeFileSync("analysis_summary.txt", summary, "utf8");
+console.log(JSON.stringify({ rows: N, overall_response: overall, iterations: iterations.length }, null, 2));

